      modelAnswer: 'Energy enters most ecosystems as light absorbed by photosynthetic producers (autotrophs), which convert about 1–3% of incident light into chemical energy in biomass (gross primary production, GPP). After deduction of energy used in respiration, net primary production (NPP) is the energy available to consumers. Producers are eaten by primary consumers (herbivores), which are eaten by secondary consumers (carnivores), and so on. At each transfer, energy is lost: not all biomass is consumed (some is uneaten or lost as faeces), not all consumed biomass is assimilated, and a large fraction of assimilated energy is dissipated as heat from respiration. Typically only about 10% of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next, although this varies (closer to 20% in some fish, less in mammals). This loss explains why food chains rarely have more than four or five trophic levels — there is not enough energy left to support higher predators in stable populations. Pyramids of energy quantify these losses and are always upright. The inefficiency of energy transfer also has agricultural implications: humans gain more energy from eating plants directly than from eating animals fed on plants. Increasing efficiency through intensive rearing or feed conversion raises ethical and environmental concerns, including animal welfare, antibiotic use and greenhouse gas emissions. The energy lost as heat is no longer available for life — it is a one-way flow from sun, through producers, consumers and decomposers, ultimately to space. Energy must therefore be continuously supplied by photosynthesis to maintain life, while matter is recycled. Understanding energy flow underlies ecosystem ecology, conservation, agriculture and discussions about sustainable diets and land use.'
