      modelAnswer: 'Homeostasis is the maintenance of relatively constant internal conditions despite external change, allowing enzymes to function near optimum and cells to remain in osmotic balance. Negative feedback is the central mechanism: a deviation from the set point is detected by receptors, processed by a control centre and corrected by effectors that return the system to the set point. The change itself triggers responses that oppose it. In thermoregulation, hypothalamic thermoreceptors detect blood temperature; if it rises, sweating, vasodilation and reduced metabolic rate cool the body; if it falls, shivering, vasoconstriction and increased metabolic rate raise temperature. Behavioural responses (clothing, shelter) reinforce physiological responses. Body temperature is held within ~36.5–37.5 °C. In blood glucose control, the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas detect blood glucose. After eating, β cells secrete insulin, which binds receptors on liver, muscle and fat cells, triggering insertion of GLUT4 transporters, glycogen synthesis, increased respiration and fat synthesis; blood glucose falls. During fasting or exercise, α cells secrete glucagon, causing the liver to break down glycogen and synthesise glucose from amino acids, releasing it into the blood. Adrenaline reinforces glucagon\'s effect during stress. Both systems show key features: reference values, sensors, integrators and antagonistic effectors. Negative feedback always lags behind the disturbance — it corrects rather than prevents change — but is sensitive, sustainable and capable of handling multiple variables. Failure leads to disease: disrupted thermoregulation causes hypo/hyperthermia, while diabetes results from failed glucose control. Positive feedback (childbirth, action potentials) drives change to completion but is unstable; the body uses it sparingly. Negative feedback therefore underpins the dynamic stability that makes complex life possible.'
