      modelAnswer: 'Both systems coordinate body responses but differ in mechanism, speed, duration and specificity. The nervous system uses electrical impulses along neurones and chemical signals at synapses; the endocrine system uses chemical hormones secreted by glands directly into the blood. Nervous responses are fast (milliseconds), short-lived, highly localised and discrete. Endocrine responses are slower (seconds to hours), longer-lasting, and may affect many tissues simultaneously, depending on which cells have appropriate receptors. Examples: a withdrawal reflex (touching a hot object) is coordinated by the nervous system because speed is essential; long-term changes in metabolism, growth, water balance, blood glucose and reproductive cycles are coordinated by the endocrine system because duration and broad targets matter. The two systems often work together: the hypothalamus links them, controlling the pituitary and so most other endocrine glands; adrenaline (endocrine) reinforces sympathetic nervous responses to stress; emotional centres in the brain influence hormone release; circulating hormones modulate brain activity. Both systems use chemical signals at the molecular level (neurotransmitters and hormones) but differ in delivery: down a wire or through the bloodstream. Together they provide complementary control: rapid, precise nervous responses for moment-to-moment behaviour; slower, sustained endocrine responses for development, reproduction and homeostasis. Disorders of either system illustrate how integrated they are: hypothalamic damage disrupts pituitary function and downstream endocrine, vegetative and emotional behaviour. Recognising the two systems as a connected neuroendocrine network gives a more accurate picture of how the body coordinates complex behaviour and adaptation.'
