      modelAnswer: 'Sanger sequencing was the original method: a region of DNA is amplified, then a sequencing reaction is set up containing a primer, DNA polymerase, normal dNTPs and small amounts of dideoxynucleotides (ddNTPs), each labelled with a different fluorescent dye. As polymerase extends the primer, it occasionally incorporates a ddNTP, terminating the chain. The result is a mixture of fragments of every length, each ending with a labelled ddNTP whose colour identifies the terminating base. Capillary electrophoresis separates fragments by length, and a laser reads off the colour at each length, giving the base sequence. Modern next-generation sequencing (NGS) uses parallel sequencing of millions of fragments at once, dropping cost from $3 billion (Human Genome Project) to under $1000 today. Applications in medicine: personalised medicine — sequencing a tumour identifies driver mutations, guiding targeted therapy (e.g. trastuzumab for HER2-positive breast cancer, imatinib for BCR-ABL leukaemia); pharmacogenomics — variants in genes such as CYP2D6 affect drug metabolism, allowing dose individualisation; inherited disease — sequencing identifies mutations causing rare diseases, often ending diagnostic odysseys; non-invasive prenatal testing analyses foetal DNA in maternal blood; newborn screening detects treatable conditions. Infectious disease — rapid sequencing of pathogen genomes tracks outbreaks (Ebola, COVID-19), reveals antibiotic resistance and informs vaccine design. Population genomics — large biobanks (UK Biobank, 100,000 Genomes Project) link genome to disease. Challenges include data storage and analysis, interpretation of variants of uncertain significance, equitable access (most reference data are European), data privacy and incidental findings. Genome sequencing is moving rapidly into routine clinical practice and promises to reshape medicine.'
